<section class="case-chapter" data-chapter="takeaway">
  <h2>Remember</h2>
  <div class="case-takeaway">
    <h3>Key takeaways</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <div class="tone-junior">Attach one listener to the parent, not one listener per child — events bubble up, so the parent hears all clicks from its descendants.</div>
        <div class="tone-mid">event.target.closest(selector) is the delegation primitive — it finds the nearest ancestor matching your selector from the clicked element up.</div>
        <div class="tone-staff">React delegates all events to the root already — adding native addEventListener per item fights the framework. Use React event props and rely on its delegation.</div>
      </li>
      <li>
        <div class="tone-junior">Delegation handles dynamically-added elements automatically — no need to re-bind when adding, filtering, or sorting rows.</div>
        <div class="tone-mid">For non-bubbling events (focus, blur): use focusin/focusout instead — they bubble and are delegation-compatible.</div>
        <div class="tone-staff">Memory leak prevention: removing the parent container removes the single listener. Per-row listeners require explicit cleanup on each removed row to avoid leaks.</div>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</section>
